      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What's the most important SEO tool for a law firm?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Google Business Profile (free). It controls Map Pack visibility for attorney searches. If unclaimed or unoptimized, no paid tool compensates. After GBP, content creation tools have the highest ranking impact — publishing 30 articles monthly targeting queries like "how much does a personal injury lawyer cost" generates more consultations than weekly rank tracking without content.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should a law firm spend on SEO tools?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Solo practitioners: $50–150/month. Small firms (2–10 attorneys): $200–400/month. Mid-size firms (10–50 attorneys): $500–1,000/month. Track cost per client acquired, not just total tool spending. At $99–126/month, theStacc delivers 30 articles monthly — more content than most legal SEO agencies at $2,000–10,000/month.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does SEO take to work for law firms?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">60–90 days for initial ranking movement. 6–12 months for consistent organic traffic. Legal keywords are highly competitive. "Personal injury lawyer [major city]" may require 12–18 months. Long-tail queries like "how to file workers comp claim in [state]" can rank in 60–90 days.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do lawyers need local SEO or regular SEO?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Both. Local SEO (GBP, citations, reviews, Map Pack) drives high-intent "lawyer near me" searches. Regular SEO (blog content, practice area pages, long-tail keywords) drives informational queries that convert to consultations. Combined approach separates page-one firms from invisible competitors.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What legal keywords should I target first?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Start with high-intent location queries: "[practice area] lawyer [city]," "[practice area] attorney near me," "free consultation [practice area] [city]." Then expand to informational queries: "how much does [practice area] lawyer cost," "what to expect during [legal process]," "statute of limitations for [claim type] in [state]."</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is review management really that important for lawyers?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Yes. 84% of people trust online reviews as much as personal referrals when choosing a lawyer. Google's algorithm uses review signals (volume, rating, recency) for Map Pack rankings. Firms with 100+ reviews and 4.8+ ratings outrank comparable firms with fewer reviews.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should lawyers do SEO themselves or hire an agency?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Neither alone is ideal. Agencies charge $2,000–10,000/month with generic content. DIY costs $2,000–5,000/month in lost billable time at $200–500/hour. Better approach: automated tools for content and GBP (theStacc at $99–126/month), plus 2–3 hours monthly for strategy review.</div>
